<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-078-872  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 078 872.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Jan 22 1990 v24 n4 p71(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>New net feathers poultry giant's nest. (Tyson Foods Inc.'snationwide computer network) (company profile)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Booker, Ellis.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Tyson Foods Inc, the largest poultry-processing company in the US,will spend $9.2 million through 1992 to replace its nationwidenetwork made up of a Unisys 1100/92 mainframe and Unix-basedcomputers in the field with a system using two DEC VAX 6420s andMicrovax 3100 workstations connected on a 60-node Ethernetnetwork.andP;  The company's current system uses mixed hardware,software and communications equipment, but it is hoped that theVAXs will lead to more distributed computing applications.andP;  Tysonwill almost double in size as the result of its 1989 acquisitionof Holly Farms Corp from $2.3 billion to $4 billion.andP;  Unisys, IBMand DEC competed for the contract for the new system; DEC waschosen after it scored highest on a 26-point evaluation form, butthe company's reputation for networking was important consideringTyson's need to connect its 13 remote 'complexes'.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Tyson Foods Inc. (data processing).andO;Ticker:    TYSND.andO;Product:   DEC VAX 6420 (Minicomputer) (business use).andO;Topic:     EthernetApplicationsFood IndustryDistributed SystemsWide Area NetworksMinicomputers.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>